title: For Sale/Trade:  Very Early WWII Colt M1911-A1 All Original w/extras
postcontent: Up for sale is this wonderful example of a very early USGI (United States Government Issue) W.W.I.I. Military Sidearm.  This is a completely original M1911-A1 manufactured by Colt (The original designer and builder of the 1911).  This particular pistol was built and shipped between July 18th and 31st of 1941.  This pistols S/N of 736XXX is right at the point of production where they went from being blued to being parkerized.  It comes with what I believe to be its original service holster, belt, magazine pouch magazine.  There are 4 magazines included and I also have 3 boxes of USGI surplus ammo.  The story I have is this M1911-A1 was originally issued to a Private Raymond L Carson  of the 326th Engineering Corp. (his was SN36376557).  Private Carson entered the service from Michigan and was KIA in Germany on September, 18 1944.  He is buried in the American Cemetery and Memorial in Limburg, Netherlands.  This pistol is in very good condition showing very little wear and/or scratching.  Has all original parts it was issued with that include the correct "Hollow-Back" grips, the small "G" stamped barrel correct Colt manufactured trigger, hammer, slide release, thumb safety, grip safety and main spring housing.  There are 2 original early W.W.I.I. Colt Manufactured 7-round magazines (marked "Colt 45 Auto." on the base).  The original Boyt 42 Holster has it's lanyard braided (most likely done by Pvt. Carson), the belt has Private Carson's information written in it and is in near perfect condition, the magazine pouch is the original Boyle 42 that has 2 slightly later issue pinned base magazines in it. (1 shows some rust pitting but operates perfectly).  I have also found a reproduction of the original shipping box and wax protective paper inside.  I have 3 boxes of USGI Issued .45 ammo that are in unopened boxes dated 5-44 and 7-44.  I am selling everything as a package.  The Colt M1911-A1 with (4) Correct W.W.I.I. Magazines pinned-base (2 are marked Colt 45), Holster, Mag Pouch, Belt, 3 boxes of W.W.I.I. issued ammo and reproduction shipping box.  This is a REAL COLT that I am asking $3850.00 for the entire package and I will not separate any of it.  I will consider trades (Whole or partial) of collector Colt 1911's or Revolvers and may consider a S&W.  Send me your contact information with a phone number and I'll get back to you.  If you send a message and it does not include your contact information I'll assume you're a scammer and I will not reply.  I live in Albuquerque, NM and I am willing to ship and insure at the expense of the buyer.  If your FFL will not accept a shipment from an individual with 2 forms of ID I will ask that you pay the $25 FFL on my end.

This pistol is in very good condition showing very little wear and/or scratching. postcontent:
Tactical and Military Sporter models are manufactured by combining original Sa vz. 58 components with a new semi-auto only milled receiver, a new trigger mechanism and new fire controls.

Currently it is still the standard issue service rifle in both the Czech Republic and Slovakia.

7.62x39mm Adjustable rear sights, Wood-impregnated plastic stock 

Magazine Capacity 30 

Magazine Type Detachable 

Weight 6.410 lbs 

Barrel Length 16.140” Overall length 35”

Stock Wood-impregnated Plastic 

Stock Type Military 

Sights Rear adjustable, hooded front

Advantages of Sa vz. 58 over AK47 rifles
•	All vz. 58 rifles possess a milled receiver; the vast majority of AK47s utilize stamped sheet metal receivers and are not as rigid as the vz.58 receiver. 
•	Even with the milled receiver it is almost one pound lighter than a stamped AK47. 
•	The bolt of the vz. 58 stays open after the last round in the magazine has been fired – the shooter immediately knows the firearm is empty and allows for quicker reloads. 
•	The vz. 58 can be reloaded with stripper clips while the magazine is inserted in the rifle. 
•	The vz. 58 has a more natural point of aim and is faster handling. 
•	The safety is more ergonomic making a faster first shot possible with the vz. 58. Unlike the AK safety, the vz. 58 safety can be operated by just a forefinger with the hand remaining on the pistol grip.
